<span id="freeTextContainer10491279512650571964">Thought I&apos;d give it a shot. My mom loves this series. We&apos;ll see...<br/><br/>Well, I did it. I&apos;m not a super fan of the LDS fiction genre. It&apos;s generally super cheesy and unrealistic and preachy. But I love historical fiction, and <i>Rumors of War</i> delivered a great story. Set in the years leading up to World War II, the story details the lives of members of the fictional Thomas family. The tale switches from Alex, serving a mission in Germany, to Bobbi, engaged to the perfect man (according to her family, at </span>
  <span id="freeText10491279512650571964" style="display:none">Thought I'd give it a shot. My mom loves this series. We'll see...<br /><br />Well, I did it. I'm not a super fan of the LDS fiction genre. It's generally super cheesy and unrealistic and preachy. But I love historical fiction, and <i>Rumors of War</i> delivered a great story. Set in the years leading up to World War II, the story details the lives of members of the fictional Thomas family. The tale switches from Alex, serving a mission in Germany, to Bobbi, engaged to the perfect man (according to her family, at least), to Wally, mixed up and angry teen and back again, and it was easy to read and get involved with the characters. The theme of the Church was tied into the lives of the characters in a realistic way- it is the undercurrent of everything they do, intrisically woven into each thought and decision. I enjoyed this book and will definitely pick up the second. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10491279512650571964" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
