    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2644351507" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2644351507" />
    <a title="Sandi" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10907151-sandi"><img alt="Sandi" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2644351507?book_show_action=true">Jan 02, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sandi" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sandi" href="/user/show/10907151-sandi">Sandi</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2644351507" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4714412689437648153">I&apos;ve got a lot of thoughts to process from this book. So, as per usual, this will be long winded, and mostly my thoughts on completely random things, semi related to the book. LET&apos;S JUMP IN.<br/>I&apos;ve avoided Latter-day Saint fiction for a few years. I read quite a few during my teenage years, but got burned out. I never finished the work and the glory because it just...got too long and soap opera-y. Anyway, this series was recommended to me months ago by a friend who usually only swaps romance book s</span>
  <span id="freeText4714412689437648153" style="display:none">I've got a lot of thoughts to process from this book. So, as per usual, this will be long winded, and mostly my thoughts on completely random things, semi related to the book. LET'S JUMP IN.<br />I've avoided Latter-day Saint fiction for a few years. I read quite a few during my teenage years, but got burned out. I never finished the work and the glory because it just...got too long and soap opera-y. Anyway, this series was recommended to me months ago by a friend who usually only swaps romance book suggestions with me, so that made me pause and give it thought. I guess I decided it was time to jump in.<br />I love how the author covers many different aspects of church culture (people falling away, people trying too hard, people thinking they're better than "outsiders" and blah blah blah). I actually started listening to this book on a drive to San Antonio with my family and at one point I turned to my husband and said "oh my gosh this is exactly how my mom was raised. This mentality is so real it's not even funny." If you were to ask my mom, she would tell you that, next to marrying my dad, the best thing that ever happened to her life was getting called to Peru on her mission (which is where she met my dad 😁). She got shoved way out of a bubble and got to see the real world and the people that live there. The exact opposite of how she was raised. It changed her immensely for the better. <br />ANYWAY, I actually really enjoyed the good AND bad characteristic of the Thomas family, particularly in the dad. He made my semi-feminist hackles rise (and that jerk Phil, too) (I can't tell you how many times I yelled at Bobbi to be a strong woman and stand up for herself. And she did, so I'm glad she listened to me), but I think his testimony runs deep enough to see the absurdity in some of his opinions (at least I hope it does). That guy did quite a bit of changing between the first and last chapters, and I like to think that his heart will soften more as the books continue (fingers crossed).<br />I also love how the author chose to plant a character smack in the middle of Japanese occupied Philippines. I don't think enough Americans are aware of that corner of World War II history (if you're interested, I can't recommend enough reading "We Band of Angels" to learn more about what happened with the attack on the Philippines andBataan Death March; also it's a good book so you should read it anyway) (you could also watch the HBO miniseries "The Pacific" but I can't emphasize enough how violent and SUPER sweary it is. Like, f-bombs left and right. And also real bombs... Badum ching. I'll be here all week). I've said it before and I'll say it again, if I had to be a POW during WWII with the Germans or with the Japanese, it would be the Germans all the way (I have weird trains of thought sometimes. Like, Hitler's Germany would be way more pleasant than Stalin's Russia. But only just). <br />I also found it interesting that there was the perspective of German members of the church, and other Christians or decent Germans, who supported Hitler. You'd like to think that anyone with any goodness in them would've opposed him vehemently, but even good people can be blind. So that was interesting for me to think about and mull over. <br />One of the things that I find difficult about reading WWII books, is that I know what's going to happen and they don't and that's frustrating. I'm a freak show, I know.<br /><br />Well, this review didn't really make any sense at all in terms of officially reviewing a book, so I guess in conclusion, I liked it! I forsee many tears shed in my future for this family. I'm going to read like, ten regency romances as a unicorn chaser after I'm done with this series.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4714412689437648153" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


